03980nam a22005055i 9780773575608DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735756087 a10.1515/97807735756082doi  a(DE-B1597)657085  a(OCoLC)1320874408  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLC1037 ǂb L43 2007eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a331.702/3309711 aLehmann, Wolfgang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChoosing to Labour? :bSchool-Work Transitions and Social Class /cWolfgang Lehmann. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b23 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tWhen Structure Met Agency -- tInstitutional Context: “And It Was Kind of Hard to Get Information” -- tGender: “Men Work, Women Have Children” -- tSocial Context: “It’s Just What My Family Does” -- tThe Role of Policy: “We’re Supposed To Be Learning” -- tThe Role of Theory: Choosing to Labour? -- tAppendices -- tProfile of Participants -- tData and Methodology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYoung people about to leave high school argue that they are determining their own destinies. Scholarly debates also suggest that the influence of structural factors such as social class on an individual's life course is decreasing. Wolfgang Lehmann challenges this view and offers a detailed comparative analysis of the inter-relationships between social class, institutional structures, and individual educational and career choices. Through a qualitative study of academic-track high school students and participants in youth apprenticeships in Germany and Canada, Lehmann shows how the range of available school-work transition options are defined by both gender and social class. Highlighting the importance of the institutional context in understanding school-work transitions, particularly in relation to Germany's celebrated apprenticeship system, which rests on highly streamed secondary schooling and a stratified labour market, Lehmann argues that social inequalities are maintained in part by the choices made by young people, rather than simply by structural forces. Choosing to Labour? concludes with an exploration of how public policy can meet the dual challenge of providing young people with meaningful and equitable educational experiences, while simultaneously fulfilling the need for a skilled workforce.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357560840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773575608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773575608/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles